{"questionId":"31769517","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Olivia’s house consists of four vertical walls and a sloping roof made from two rectangles. The height, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{CD}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>CD</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, from the ground to the base of the roof is 4.5 m.</p>\n<p>The base angles of the roof are <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{B}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{C}} = 27^\\circ \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>B</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msup>\n    <mn>27</mn>\n    <mo>∘</mo>\n  </msup>\n</math></span> and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{C}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{B}} = 26^\\circ \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>C</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>B</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msup>\n    <mn>26</mn>\n    <mo>∘</mo>\n  </msup>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/11d726ebf724779378ad11ab96ea9ccddff3e9ce.png\"></p>\n<p>The&nbsp;house is 10 m long and 5 m wide.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The length <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AC}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AC</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> is approximately 2.84 m.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Olivia decides to put solar panels on the roof. The solar panels are fitted to both sides of the roof.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/c49ecb1fe74add5ed7a3392bbf1cbdf575411e02.png\"></p>\n<p>Each&nbsp;panel is 1.6 m long and 0.95 m wide. All the panels must be arranged in uniform rows, with <strong>the shorter edge</strong> of each panel parallel to <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AB}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AB</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> or <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AC}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AC</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>. Each panel must be at least 0.3 m from the edge of the roof and the top of the roof, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AF}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AF</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the maximum number of complete panels that can be fitted to the whole roof.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{10 - 2\\left( {0.3} \\right)}}{{1.6}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>10</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>0.3</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1.6</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct calculation of the number of panels on the long side.</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{2.745 - 2\\left( {0.3} \\right)}}{{0.95}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>2.745</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>0.3</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>0.95</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;</strong> <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{2.84 - 2\\left( {0.3} \\right)}}{{0.95}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>2.84</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mn>0.3</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>0.95</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct calculation of the number of panels on either short side with no further incorrect working.</p>\n<p>20&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong><em><strong>(G2)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (a). Do not award <em><strong>(M0)(M1)</strong><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong><em>[3 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"31769517","referenceCode":"19M.2.SL.TZ1.T_2c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the maximum number of complete panels that can be fitted to the whole roof.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Prior learning","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, distance, midpoints","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}